<div type="edition" xml:lang="tam-Latn" rendition="class:tamil maturity:vernacular">

<p>
<lb n="1–2"/><hi rend="grantha">svasti śrī</hi> {<hi rend="grantha">meykkīrtti</hi>}
<lb n="3"/>{<hi rend="grantha">meykkīrtti</hi>} koppara {layer of black grease} Uttuṅka <gap reason="lost" quantity="5" unit="character"/> nāṭākiya kuṉṟakkūṟṟattu <hi rend="grantha">brahmade</hi>yam ciṟupaḻuvūr tiruvālantuṟaiy Āḻvār nilam<note>The -<hi rend="grantha">la</hi> was added under the –<hi rend="grantha">m</hi>, perhaps because it had been forgotten.</note> coṟṟi kuṭuttu ‡ pāṇṭārattu ‡ Irinta kācil Ikkoyil <hi rend="grantha">śrī</hi> koyiluṭaiyom koṇṭa kācu 15 Ikkācu patiṉ Aiñtum koṇṭu comittāl ne ‡ yyamutu ‡ potu
<lb n="4"/>Oru piṭiyāka nicatam muppiṭi neyyamutu ce<unclear>y</unclear>taru<unclear>ḷa</unclear> {layer of black grease} <unclear>Itu</unclear><hi rend="grantha">cantraditya</hi>val <hi rend="grantha">panmāheśvara rakṣai</hi> ||
</p>

</div>

<div type="apparatus">

</div>

<div type="translation" source="bib:Gillet2024_01">

<p>Fortune! Prosperity! {<foreign>meykkīrtti</foreign>} <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Having given <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>kuṭuttu</foreign></supplied> a land <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>nilam</foreign></supplied><note>It is difficult to make sense of the word<foreign>coṟṟi</foreign> / <foreign>cōṟṟi</foreign>, which is after <foreign>nilam</foreign>. I thus did not attempt to translate it.</note> <supplied reason="subaudible">to</supplied> the Lord <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>āḻvār</foreign></supplied> of Tiruvālantuṟai of Ciṟupaḻuvūr, a <foreign>brahmadeya</foreign> of Kuṉṟakkūṟṟam alias Uttuṅka<supplied reason="lost">tuṅkavaḷa</supplied>nāṭu; from the <foreign>kācu</foreign>s <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>kācil</foreign></supplied> which stay <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>irinta</foreign> &gt; <foreign>irunta</foreign></supplied> in the accountant office <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pāṇṭāram</foreign></supplied>, we the Śrīkkōyiluṭaiyars of this temple <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>ikkōyil</foreign></supplied> took <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>koṇṭa</foreign></supplied> 15 <foreign>kācu</foreign>s; having taken <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>koṇṭu</foreign></supplied> these fiteen <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>patiṉ</foreign> <foreign>aiñtum &gt; aiñcum</foreign></supplied> <foreign>kācu</foreign>s, to graciously make <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>ceytaruḷa</foreign></supplied> three handfuls <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>mūppiṭi</foreign></supplied> of <foreign>ghee</foreign> food offerings <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>neyyamutu</foreign></supplied> everyday <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>nicatam</foreign></supplied> as <supplied reason="subaudible">i.e. at the rate of</supplied> <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>āka</foreign></supplied> one handful <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>oru piṭi</foreign></supplied> for one time <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pōtu</foreign></supplied> of <foreign>ghee</foreign> food offerings <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>neyyamutu</foreign></supplied>.<note>I cannot make sense of<foreign>cōmittāl</foreign> or <foreign>cōḻittāl</foreign>. May it be a kind of measure for the <foreign>ghee</foreign>? </note> This is under the protection of the Panmāheśvaras, as long as the sun and the moon endure.</p></div>

